                                        ▼
                              pywhispercpp inference
                              (streaming-optimised params)
                                        │
                                        ▼
                              GLib.idle_add → emit("text", …)

Streaming parameters derived from whisper.cpp stream example
(examples/stream/stream.cpp):
  • audio_ctx       = 768   – partial encoder context (~2× faster)
  • temperature_inc = -1.0  – disable temperature fallback (no hallucinations)
  • single_segment  = True  – one output segment per window (no drift)
  • no_context      = True  – independent windows (no bleed from previous)
  • max_tokens      = 64    – cap output length on silence/noise
  • n_threads       = min(8, cpu_count)

Changes in this revision (v2):
  Bug-fix A – hallucination phrase filter used substring matching, causing
    words like "you" to kill valid sentences ("Could you please…").
    Fixed: phrases must now match the *entire* output (after stripping
    punctuation/whitespace), not appear anywhere inside it.  The word "you"
    is removed entirely — it is far too common in real speech to blacklist.

  Bug-fix B – initial_prompt + tail-buffer caused prompt injection.
    The model received _last_text="…word" as initial_prompt AND heard the
    tail-buffer audio of that same word prepended to the next segment, so
    it echoed "word word word…" in the output.  Fix: initial_prompt is now
    used only when the new segment is short (< SHORT_SEGMENT_THRESHOLD_S),
    where context genuinely helps.  For normal-length segments (≥ 2 s) the
    model is given no prompt and decodes independently.  Additionally,
    _strip_prompt_echo() removes any prefix in the output that textually
    repeats the end of the previous transcription, catching residual echoes.

  Bug-fix C – trailing word repetition loop (Hindi / long utterances).
    Added _strip_trailing_repeats() which collapses "word word word word"
    at the tail of any output down to a single occurrence.  This catches the
    Whisper pathology where it loops on the last token when context and audio
